WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:06.010
Okay. So in the interest of keeping this on time, I think we're going to go ahead

2
00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:09.340
and get started. I know people are still filtering in a little bit.

3
00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:12.980
So I'm Dr. Joshua LaBaer, and this is Dr.

4
00:00:13.220 --> 00:00:16.210
Irene Gabriel, and we're here to lead this

5
00:00:16.261 --> 00:00:19.780
session. And if I can, yep, switch to this.

6
00:00:19.900 --> 00:00:23.730
I'm going to do a couple of quickie introductory notes just because

7
00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:27.310
I've spent most of my career looking at biomarkers, and so I thought I would talk

8
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:31.270
in general a little bit about biomarkers just to set the stage for a lot of

9
00:00:31.300 --> 00:00:35.040
what we're going to hear today. So biomarkers are basically biometric

10
00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:38.840
measurements that convey some kind of information about the subject's either

11
00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:40.660
biological or clinical state.

12
00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:45.600
We can think about biomarkers in terms of how they're going to be

13
00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.350
used, which I think is a big part of what we'll hear today,

14
00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:53.130
where the material comes from, what type of material people are using, and

15
00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:54.200
how

16
00:00:55.100 --> 00:00:57.300
thoroughly the biomarkers are validated.

17
00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:02.700
In terms of clinical use, a common use is to stratify patients

18
00:01:02.740 --> 00:01:04.560
into specific subtypes of disease.

19
00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:08.120
You could think of the MSI status in colon cancer, for

20
00:01:08.140 --> 00:01:11.640
example. They're definitely useful for looking at

21
00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:14.440
prediction in terms of use of therapies.

22
00:01:14.470 --> 00:01:16.700
So are they a good companion diagnostic?

23
00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:21.200
We'll hear a number of examples of prognostic biomarkers, so essentially

24
00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:24.480
assessing how aggressive a cancer will be and where it will end up.

25
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:25.640
We can think about

26
00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:28.960
monitoring disease progression with biomarkers.

27
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.980
This is commonly done in cancer therapy, looking at things like CEA in colon

28
00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:34.060
cancer.

29
00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:37.630
The area that I've been interested in is early detection biomarkers.

30
00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:40.980
Can we pick up cancer before they're clinically apparent?

31
00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:44.840
And then, of course, there are markers that actually predict risk of cancer.

32
00:01:45.760 --> 00:01:46.020
So

33
00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:50.710
you can sometimes use biomarkers defined for one approach for another

34
00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:53.160
approach, but that doesn't always work great.

35
00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:57.560
So in terms of types of markers, this is a list of common

36
00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:01.360
types of markers. Obviously, today we're going to be thinking about spatiotemporal

37
00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.040
sampling. So looking at different time points

38
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:09.299
and different locations and also measuring various types of omic

39
00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:12.400
responses is what we're going to be focusing on today.

40
00:02:13.560 --> 00:02:14.520
Just as a quick note,

41
00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:19.480
the success of getting biomarkers through the FDA has not been

42
00:02:19.660 --> 00:02:23.560
stupendous. In the past 10 years, there have been five tests that have

43
00:02:23.580 --> 00:02:27.280
been cleared by the FDA for cancer detection.

44
00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:31.520
So that speaks to the challenges inherent in finding good

45
00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:35.380
biomarkers. And just to outline those, first of all,

46
00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:39.440
it's very difficult to find a difference in a biological specimen

47
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.840
that is predictive of outcome. It's especially hard to

48
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:46.360
find them in accessible fluids, and

49
00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:49.400
it's ridiculously hard to find them that are not

50
00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:53.220
affected by other related diseases.

51
00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:53.500
So,

52
00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:59.040
other things that are challenging, as many of you know, just to get these studies

53
00:02:59.100 --> 00:03:03.000
off the ground, getting the appropriate clinical samples is a

54
00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:06.860
big challenge. And probably one of the biggest challenges

55
00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:08.940
is even if you find a difference,

56
00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:13.440
getting the funding to do a validation study is

57
00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:17.470
especially challenging. You will often get reviews back on your

58
00:03:17.500 --> 00:03:21.079
grant proposals saying that this has already been done. Why are you doing it again?

59
00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:24.860
So, just to think a little bit about validation.

60
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.160
Typically, biomarker studies begin with making some kind of an observed difference

61
00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.910
between cases and controls. And if you do enough of those

62
00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:36.640
together, you will get a subset of those markers that you would think of

63
00:03:36.780 --> 00:03:40.250
as candidate biomarkers, once you define their sensitivity and

64
00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:44.200
specificity. From there, you really need to verify that biomarker

65
00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:48.140
by repeating it in a fully independent set

66
00:03:48.220 --> 00:03:52.140
of samples. So nothing in common with the previous discovery set,

67
00:03:52.600 --> 00:03:55.040
so you can be sure that they really are not false positives.

68
00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:59.460
Then you're set up to do an actual validation study, which should be a

69
00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:03.420
prospective blinded study to see if, in fact, the markers

70
00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:04.440
are truly predictive.

71
00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:08.820
After which you really need to do a utility study to show that

72
00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:12.680
by using those biomarkers, you can actually change the clinical

73
00:04:12.980 --> 00:04:16.680
benefit of-- you can improve the clinical benefit of people being

74
00:04:16.700 --> 00:04:20.120
treated. So it's a long road to get to an approved

75
00:04:20.161 --> 00:04:23.900
biomarker, and all of it depends on first defining

76
00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:27.240
what's the clinical need that you're going to address with the biomarker.

77
00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:32.000
So lots of pitfalls. Discovery without defining the clinical need,

78
00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.580
doing inappropriate statistics, doing an underpowered study,

79
00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:39.800
failure to account for overfitting, which is a huge issue in omics.

80
00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:43.880
If we're looking at lots and lots of variables, it's very easy to find something

81
00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:47.540
that doesn't hold up when you repeat the study in a different population.

82
00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:51.910
Not using the right samples, failing to develop a robust and

83
00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:55.720
reproducible assay which can be done over and over again and

84
00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:59.740
reliably, and not doing the appropriate validation studies or the

85
00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:01.960
utility studies. So today,

86
00:05:02.780 --> 00:05:06.570
just coming back to the biomarkers by clinical use, we've got a couple of great

87
00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:09.770
talks lined up for looking at disease stratification markers.

88
00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:12.280
We've got a talk looking at

89
00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:17.120
markers that are good in predicting immunotherapy response, so a

90
00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:20.520
companion diagnostic. We've got several talks on

91
00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:24.600
prognostic biomarkers and one talk on an early

92
00:05:24.660 --> 00:05:28.560
detection biomarker. So I won't spill the beans on what they're

93
00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:30.420
going to talk about since they're going to do it in a moment.

94
00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:33.480
So I just want to thank you, and we'll start with the first talk.

95
00:05:34.940 --> 00:05:38.820
All right. Thank you so much. And our first talk is on spatial transcriptomics

96
00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:42.260
profiling of colorectal cancer tumors in Alaska Native people:

97
00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.340
Discovery of prognostic biomarkers by Geryk Cheng.

98
00:05:56.260 --> 00:05:59.540
So thank you very much for coming to my talk, and thank you, AACR, for selecting my

99
00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.600
talk for this mini symposium. So today I'm going to talk about the

100
00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:07.440
spatial transcriptomic profiling of colorectal cancer samples

101
00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:11.400
in Alaska Native people and trying to discover prognostic biomarkers.

102
00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:13.680
And I have nothing to disclose.

103
00:06:16.108 --> 00:06:19.977
So colorectal cancer in Alaska Native people, this is one of the most

104
00:06:20.028 --> 00:06:23.628
commonly diagnosed cancer and there exists stark

105
00:06:23.648 --> 00:06:27.088
disparities where they are having the highest rates in the world

106
00:06:27.488 --> 00:06:31.448
compared to the US average. Their incidence rate

107
00:06:31.508 --> 00:06:34.828
is two times higher, and their mortality rates are almost three times

108
00:06:34.988 --> 00:06:38.838
higher. And these rates cannot just be explained by the screening because their

109
00:06:38.868 --> 00:06:42.688
screening rates are similar to the US public So we want to

110
00:06:42.728 --> 00:06:46.488
understand how to have the best available

111
00:06:47.088 --> 00:06:49.208
methods to increase their survivability.

112
00:06:49.248 --> 00:06:53.058
So the current knowledge gaps and barrier is that there's just a lack of

113
00:06:53.088 --> 00:06:56.658
clinically useful biomarkers and tools for predicting clinical

114
00:06:56.768 --> 00:06:59.768
outcomes that's tailored specifically for Alaska Native people.

115
00:07:00.308 --> 00:07:03.828
And as you all know, most established researchers are focusing on

116
00:07:04.028 --> 00:07:07.728
non-Hispanic white people. And by having effective prognostic

117
00:07:07.748 --> 00:07:11.448
biomarkers for them, it allows a robust risk stratification

118
00:07:11.948 --> 00:07:15.358
and preventing over or under-treatment and overall,

119
00:07:15.808 --> 00:07:17.548
increasing their survival likelihood.

120
00:07:19.908 --> 00:07:23.808
So, in order to try to find the spatial biomarkers, we

121
00:07:23.848 --> 00:07:27.728
decided to look into both the tumor and the tumor microenvironment around the

122
00:07:27.748 --> 00:07:31.408
tumor. And, just a quick definition of TME, it's the

123
00:07:31.468 --> 00:07:35.178
ecosystem surrounding the cancer cells, and they have different cell types,

124
00:07:35.228 --> 00:07:38.888
different soluble factors. And the spatial organization of these cell

125
00:07:38.968 --> 00:07:42.788
types of the tumor and TME and how their pathways are

126
00:07:43.008 --> 00:07:46.788
enriched can drive the development of the tumor, how

127
00:07:46.848 --> 00:07:47.688
the disease

128
00:07:48.668 --> 00:07:52.448
going to turn out, and also how the patient's going to respond to therapy.

129
00:07:54.228 --> 00:07:58.168
And in here we have a really unique study population,

130
00:07:58.268 --> 00:08:01.708
thanks to our close collaboration with the Alaska Native Tribal Health

131
00:08:01.748 --> 00:08:04.028
Consortium, where currently we have

132
00:08:05.168 --> 00:08:08.978
217 Alaska Native patients who have colorectal cancer, and we have

133
00:08:09.028 --> 00:08:13.018
their FFP tissue blocks. And, the patients who die from colorectal

134
00:08:13.068 --> 00:08:16.768
cancer are matched one to two to patients who did not die from

135
00:08:16.788 --> 00:08:20.398
colorectal cancer. And, these data have been

136
00:08:21.248 --> 00:08:24.708
processed with GeoMix and additional 100

137
00:08:24.768 --> 00:08:28.328
patients are also being generated with GeoMix data that we will be

138
00:08:28.388 --> 00:08:30.268
including in our results in the future.

139
00:08:31.028 --> 00:08:31.248
And,

140
00:08:32.528 --> 00:08:36.088
for these tissue blocks, we will then extract tissue cores for them

141
00:08:36.288 --> 00:08:38.948
and arrange them into tissue microarrays.

142
00:08:39.428 --> 00:08:43.389
And apart from GeoMix, we also have other spatial

143
00:08:43.428 --> 00:08:47.068
omics profiling performed on them, including bulk

144
00:08:47.148 --> 00:08:51.048
RNA-seq, PhenoCyte, which is single cell spatial proteomics, and also

145
00:08:51.108 --> 00:08:53.328
Xenia, which is single cell spatial transcriptomics.

146
00:08:53.968 --> 00:08:55.998
And, this one is our

147
00:08:56.988 --> 00:09:00.818
characteristics of our study population, which also includes

148
00:09:00.848 --> 00:09:04.658
matched on sex, tumor stage, and

149
00:09:04.688 --> 00:09:05.268
tumor sites.

150
00:09:07.588 --> 00:09:10.728
So, the way that we have our different cores is that we first,

151
00:09:12.128 --> 00:09:16.028
for each patient, we identify cores that are two cores

152
00:09:16.068 --> 00:09:18.868
from tumor center and then one core from the invasive margin.

153
00:09:19.258 --> 00:09:23.098
And then for each core, we also have identified the epithelium and the

154
00:09:23.148 --> 00:09:26.188
stroma, which corresponds to the tumor and TME

155
00:09:26.208 --> 00:09:29.988
respectively. And we're using the pencillin marker to

156
00:09:30.028 --> 00:09:33.988
identify the different regions, and we also have pathologists to verify that.

157
00:09:34.328 --> 00:09:38.308
And in total, we have 1,140 total tissue

158
00:09:38.348 --> 00:09:41.748
compartments that is currently used for the GeoMix analysis.

159
00:09:43.508 --> 00:09:47.308
And, as I mentioned, we're using GeoMix, and the specific part

160
00:09:47.348 --> 00:09:51.048
about that is that it allows for a UV-dependent cleavage of the

161
00:09:51.068 --> 00:09:53.928
oligo-labeled RNA probes. So since we know where the

162
00:09:54.688 --> 00:09:58.408
epithelial segment and the stromal segment is, we can then just shine the UV light

163
00:09:58.448 --> 00:10:02.108
onto there, and then it can release the RNA probes, so we're able to know the

164
00:10:02.208 --> 00:10:05.808
spatially specific transcriptomic profiles of those tissue

165
00:10:05.828 --> 00:10:06.368
compartments.

166
00:10:08.368 --> 00:10:10.908
And the bioinformatic pipeline is relatively straightforward.

167
00:10:11.028 --> 00:10:14.968
We first have quality control, where we kick out any segments and genes that are

168
00:10:15.388 --> 00:10:19.268
underperforming. And then we also have batch effects correction, as our data

169
00:10:19.328 --> 00:10:21.977
is being processed in different batches.

170
00:10:22.348 --> 00:10:25.988
We want to make sure all the differences that remains are from biological

171
00:10:26.008 --> 00:10:28.868
differences and not experimental differences.

172
00:10:28.948 --> 00:10:32.648
So, we did the batch effect correction for that, and then we also did

173
00:10:32.688 --> 00:10:36.258
normalization to make sure every gene's in an equal footing and easier for

174
00:10:36.267 --> 00:10:40.198
comparison. And then finally, we have the downstream analysis, including

175
00:10:40.208 --> 00:10:43.777
differential gene expression, gene set enrichment, and also cell type

176
00:10:43.808 --> 00:10:44.388
compositions.

177
00:10:46.188 --> 00:10:49.728
And for the results. So, first we have the differentially expressed

178
00:10:49.808 --> 00:10:52.928
genes. So we are able to identify spatially

179
00:10:53.288 --> 00:10:54.188
compartment-specific

180
00:10:55.188 --> 00:10:58.978
expressed genes. So specifically for the epithelial compartment of the

181
00:10:59.068 --> 00:11:02.888
tumor center, we see that for the patients who did not die from colorectal

182
00:11:02.928 --> 00:11:06.608
cancer, there is a upregulation of SPINK4 and MUQ2

183
00:11:06.648 --> 00:11:10.448
genes. And then for the epithelial compartment of the invasive margin,

184
00:11:10.808 --> 00:11:14.588
we see a upregulation of HBA2 for patients who die from colorectal

185
00:11:14.628 --> 00:11:18.268
cancer. And all these differentially expressed genes are

186
00:11:18.308 --> 00:11:22.208
being processed by using DESeq2, and then

187
00:11:22.468 --> 00:11:26.028
it's being adjusted for all the measuring co-variables I mentioned in the study

188
00:11:26.068 --> 00:11:29.308
population, including sex, tumor stage, tumor site,

189
00:11:29.568 --> 00:11:33.548
age, and year of diagnosis. And we also did

190
00:11:33.608 --> 00:11:37.508
a randomization to make sure we don't have any effects

191
00:11:37.548 --> 00:11:38.388
of the outliers.

192
00:11:39.988 --> 00:11:43.868
And once we have the results from the differentially expressed genes, we can

193
00:11:43.948 --> 00:11:47.888
then also try to see which specific pathways are being

194
00:11:47.928 --> 00:11:50.368
enriched. And, two things to note here.

195
00:11:50.568 --> 00:11:54.068
One thing is that we've identified that in the epithelial compartment,

196
00:11:54.468 --> 00:11:58.008
in both tumor center and the invasive margin, there is an

197
00:12:00.268 --> 00:12:04.128
enriched pathway of the interferon alpha and gamma response for

198
00:12:04.168 --> 00:12:07.884
patients who did not die from colorectal cancer.And

199
00:12:07.924 --> 00:12:11.644
that definitely makes sense. And also we see that in invasive margin,

200
00:12:12.044 --> 00:12:15.944
we see that both epithelial and stromal compartment, there is an

201
00:12:15.964 --> 00:12:19.924
upregulation of epithelial-mesenchymal transition-related pathways

202
00:12:19.964 --> 00:12:22.824
that are being enriched for patients who die from colorectal cancer.

203
00:12:23.224 --> 00:12:27.044
And that also makes sense because as EMT is being known for

204
00:12:27.584 --> 00:12:31.384
epithelial cells losing their cell identity and getting more fluid

205
00:12:31.444 --> 00:12:34.484
and easy to get metastasized. So it also makes sense why they are being

206
00:12:34.524 --> 00:12:37.224
upregulated for patients who die from colorectal cancer.

207
00:12:39.224 --> 00:12:41.294
And, also we are

208
00:12:43.044 --> 00:12:46.904
able to determine these pathways based on the reference database

209
00:12:46.944 --> 00:12:49.303
using Homologene, KEGG MEDica, and Reactome.

210
00:12:51.904 --> 00:12:55.384
And then after that, we also have cell type deconvolution results, where we are

211
00:12:55.464 --> 00:12:59.364
able to look at the cell type abundance score for

212
00:12:59.444 --> 00:13:00.864
the specific tissue compartments.

213
00:13:01.284 --> 00:13:05.204
And this cell type abundance score is being determined

214
00:13:05.604 --> 00:13:09.524
by using SpatialDecon, a publicly available library specifically for

215
00:13:09.564 --> 00:13:11.234
geomix results. And we're

216
00:13:12.204 --> 00:13:15.874
doing this with a custom cell reference based on a publicly

217
00:13:15.924 --> 00:13:18.884
available colorectal cancer single-cell RNA sequencing datasets.

218
00:13:19.294 --> 00:13:22.364
And what we can see in here is that for the epithelial compartment at the tumor

219
00:13:22.444 --> 00:13:26.434
center, we see an increase of plasma cells for patients who did not

220
00:13:26.434 --> 00:13:30.014
die from colorectal cancer. And for the stromal compartment of the tumor center,

221
00:13:30.404 --> 00:13:34.194
we see that an increase of mast cells for patients who die from colorectal

222
00:13:34.264 --> 00:13:38.204
cancer. And just to have a quick validation to make sure our cell deconvolution

223
00:13:38.224 --> 00:13:41.864
results are valid, we also check it with the

224
00:13:41.904 --> 00:13:45.644
consensus molecular subtypes we determine with our bulk RNA-seq

225
00:13:45.684 --> 00:13:49.624
results. And in CMS1, which is known for MSI-H, having

226
00:13:49.704 --> 00:13:53.564
a higher immune activity, we see that there is a higher immune cell type

227
00:13:53.624 --> 00:13:54.584
in those groups, so

228
00:13:56.144 --> 00:14:00.004
meaning that our cell type deconvolution results are valid.

229
00:14:01.564 --> 00:14:05.364
So in summary, our analysis have identified spatially specific markers

230
00:14:05.384 --> 00:14:08.954
that's tied to colorectal cancer-specific mortality in Alaska Native

231
00:14:09.044 --> 00:14:12.684
people. Specifically, in the tumor center, we have a

232
00:14:12.704 --> 00:14:16.404
downregulation of MILK2, SPINK4, and the interferon

233
00:14:16.464 --> 00:14:19.104
alpha and gamma pathways in the epithelial compartment.

234
00:14:19.604 --> 00:14:23.564
And in the cell type, we see that there is a decrease of plasma cells and an

235
00:14:23.644 --> 00:14:26.484
increase of mast cells in the tumor center.

236
00:14:27.234 --> 00:14:30.624
And also for the invasive margin, we see an increase of

237
00:14:30.744 --> 00:14:34.384
HBA2 expression in the epithelial compartment, and the overall

238
00:14:34.424 --> 00:14:38.354
invasive margin, we see an enriched epithelial-mesenchymal

239
00:14:38.424 --> 00:14:41.824
transition pathways. And for the future direction for this research, as I

240
00:14:41.864 --> 00:14:45.664
mentioned, there's still 100 more patients' data being generated for

241
00:14:45.684 --> 00:14:49.044
geomix that will be included. And also with the

242
00:14:49.604 --> 00:14:53.444
other spatial proteomics and transcriptomics data we have with our

