Well, thank you for

312
00:18:10.700 --> 00:18:14.040
Okay. The next speaker is David Routtenberg from Mesoscale

313
00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:18.080
Diagnostics, who will be talking about highly multiplexed immunoassays that

314
00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:21.980
enable the discovery of multi-marker EV surface signatures as novel

315
00:18:22.040 --> 00:18:22.680
biomarkers.

316
00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.300
Hi, thanks for coming. My name is David Routtenberg with Mesoscale,

317
00:18:31.370 --> 00:18:35.120
and I'm going to talk about a new tool, a new platform that we've put

318
00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:39.040
together to enable discovery of multi-marker extracellular vesicle

319
00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:41.920
surface signatures, and how we can use these as biomarkers.

320
00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.960
So I'm an employee of MSD, neither a shareholder nor an officer.

321
00:18:49.300 --> 00:18:51.700
Okay, so I'll give a little bit of background on EVs, but I know most of you

322
00:18:51.780 --> 00:18:55.740
probably know most of this info. So extracellular vesicles

323
00:18:55.820 --> 00:18:59.480
are lipid bilayer vesicles. They're secreted by all cells.

324
00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:01.500
They show up in all biofluids.

325
00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:08.460
They're typically secreted at higher levels from tumor tissue than healthy

326
00:19:08.480 --> 00:19:11.320
tissue, so that helps us if we're looking for tumor biomarkers.

327
00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:16.040
And they provide a snapshot of the originating

328
00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:19.840
cell. And so that makes them an attractive liquid biopsy target.

329
00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:24.200
We're interested in surface signatures because the surface markers reveal

330
00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:26.580
information about the cellular origin.

331
00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:31.000
They help determine the destination, ultimately, which cells will take these up, as

332
00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:33.860
well as they give us clues about the effector function of these EVs.

333
00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:37.680
And we're interested in multi-marker signatures

334
00:19:38.580 --> 00:19:42.160
because typically, single markers aren't sufficient in order to

335
00:19:42.180 --> 00:19:44.930
distinguish a lot of the interesting EV populations.

336
00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:48.940
Just as in flow cytometry, where you need two or three or more

337
00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:53.460
surface stains in order to define your interesting cell populations, it's no

338
00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:55.080
different with EVs.

339
00:19:56.980 --> 00:20:00.380
All right. So I'll use an example here to show why I think you should care about EV

340
00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:04.240
surface markers. So looking at colorectal cancer, we had a

341
00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:07.980
set of stage four patients, and we measured soluble

342
00:20:08.480 --> 00:20:12.280
CEA, sort of a classic soluble biomarker for colorectal cancer.

343
00:20:12.820 --> 00:20:16.360
And then we also measured that same CEA molecule on the surface of extracellular

344
00:20:16.460 --> 00:20:19.620
vesicles. It's actually a multi-marker signature, but it contains the CEA

345
00:20:20.340 --> 00:20:23.980
molecule. And what we found is that 16% of the

346
00:20:24.020 --> 00:20:27.930
patients were undetectable by the soluble CEA biomarker, and

347
00:20:27.960 --> 00:20:31.920
yet were detectable looking at that same molecule on the surface

348
00:20:31.940 --> 00:20:35.480
of the EVs. So clearly, there's orthogonal information

349
00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:39.900
in these two different measurements, despite being based on measuring the same

350
00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:40.860
molecule.

351
00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:42.580
So

352
00:20:43.720 --> 00:20:45.440
that kind of gives an idea of why we should care.

353
00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:47.620
The challenging thing now is to know which

354
00:20:48.660 --> 00:20:51.360
EV populations or subpopulations we should be looking at.

355
00:20:52.340 --> 00:20:55.000
So one way that you could do that would be to take a whole bunch of different

356
00:20:55.060 --> 00:20:58.540
surface markers and look at all the combinations of those surface markers and

357
00:20:58.580 --> 00:21:00.740
figure out which ones are of interest.

358
00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.740
That's challenging to do using

359
00:21:05.740 --> 00:21:09.549
typical EV assay measurements. So we developed

360
00:21:10.180 --> 00:21:11.280
a new platform for this.

361
00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:14.420
We call it combinatorial immunosequencing.

362
00:21:15.460 --> 00:21:19.260
So we essentially capture EVs from a sample on a solid phase.

363
00:21:19.820 --> 00:21:23.480
We label those EVs using a cocktail of detection antibodies,

364
00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:27.340
where each of these antibodies is tagged with a

365
00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:28.420
molecular barcode.

366
00:21:29.500 --> 00:21:33.020
We then have an assay where if three of these antibodies are

367
00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:36.700
co-localized on the same vesicle, those barcodes get stitched

368
00:21:36.740 --> 00:21:38.880
together into a sequenceable amplicon.

369
00:21:39.440 --> 00:21:41.940
And so we can then put this into an NGS.

370
00:21:42.860 --> 00:21:45.800
We can read out all the combinations of three

371
00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:50.180
surface markers that were present, along with their relative

372
00:21:50.220 --> 00:21:51.980
abundances in the sample.

373
00:21:55.240 --> 00:21:58.700
All right. So to show that this is actually reporting sensibly, we ran it on a

374
00:21:58.740 --> 00:21:59.680
number of cell lines.

375
00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:05.000
Here I'm showing four. But we found that in each case, we're able to pick

376
00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:08.780
out combinations of multiple surface markers, these triplets

377
00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:13.210
that are both highly enriched in that cell line relative to all the other cell

378
00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:16.960
lines in our little universe of cell lines, and also those that are highly

379
00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:20.679
abundant on those targets. So those would be the ones in the upper right corner.

380
00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:25.240
And what's interesting is we can take two colorectal carcinoma cell lines, so

381
00:22:25.380 --> 00:22:29.160
Diffi and HCT15, and those would be really challenging to

382
00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:32.600
separate just using a single marker because they do share a lot of the same surface

383
00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:36.690
features. But we can easily find triplet combinations that

384
00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:40.670
discriminate these quite well. So doing

385
00:22:40.670 --> 00:22:44.460
this on cell lines is relatively easy, but the kicker is can we do

386
00:22:44.520 --> 00:22:48.040
this in human biofluids? Can we detect these low abundance

387
00:22:48.640 --> 00:22:52.620
multi-marker combinations against the background of billions of

388
00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:56.670
irrelevant vesicles, or at least relevant to other biology vesicles in

389
00:22:56.720 --> 00:22:57.620
something like plasma?

390
00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:02.240
So to determine whether this is reasonable, we

391
00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:05.900
purified Diffi EVs. We spiked these

392
00:23:05.940 --> 00:23:09.140
into healthy human plasma. We did a limiting

393
00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:12.500
dilution to figure out what was the minimum number of these

394
00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:16.480
spiked-in EVs that we could detect among the background from the

395
00:23:16.500 --> 00:23:19.860
healthy plasma. And we found that we can see

396
00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:21.800
about one in 10 million.

397
00:23:24.980 --> 00:23:25.120
So

398
00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:30.460
that's hard to do with single markers, but the more markers you add up in

399
00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:34.380
conjunction, the more your nonspecific background can go away, and you

400
00:23:34.420 --> 00:23:36.099
can detect these really rare populations.

401
00:23:38.280 --> 00:23:41.960
All right. So we showed that we have sensitive-- Actually, one more thing.

402
00:23:41.990 --> 00:23:45.340
We have a really nice wide dynamic range, about four logs

403
00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:47.820
of dynamic range here, so that's helpful.

404
00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.780
So now that we have sensitive and specific

405
00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:59.040
assays, we wanted to see, can these do something useful in actual patient samples?

406
00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:03.280
So we looked at three independent cohorts of colorectal cancer

407
00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:07.160
samples. The first was a cross-sectional cohort from Bob

408
00:24:07.220 --> 00:24:11.120
Coffey's lab at Vanderbilt, and then two longitudinal cohorts from

409
00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:14.582
Andy Nixon's lab at Duke.And despite being quite different

410
00:24:14.582 --> 00:24:15.292
populations,

411
00:24:16.392 --> 00:24:19.822
and different treatment, we found a lot of similar features, similar

412
00:24:20.132 --> 00:24:23.392
three-marker combinations in these three cohorts.

413
00:24:24.352 --> 00:24:27.772
And the interesting thing was that these combinations really reflect two distinct

414
00:24:27.912 --> 00:24:31.572
tumor compartments. So we have combinations that reflect the

415
00:24:31.592 --> 00:24:35.052
epithelial cells, so we can see there are combinations of markers like

416
00:24:35.112 --> 00:24:38.812
CEA, E-cadherin, EpCAM, and then we

417
00:24:39.572 --> 00:24:43.492
also see stromal combinations. And then there's a

418
00:24:43.512 --> 00:24:46.972
few things like CD73 that we know show up on both the stromal population

419
00:24:47.252 --> 00:24:51.232
and the epithelial population. So that's where if you just look at the single

420
00:24:51.272 --> 00:24:55.012
marker CD73, it's really hard to put this into one of those two compartments.

421
00:24:55.232 --> 00:24:56.172
You need the multimarker.

422
00:24:58.692 --> 00:25:01.852
All right. So to convince ourselves that what we're seeing here is not just an

423
00:25:01.942 --> 00:25:05.222
artifact of the assay, because we're a little worried that if you jam a bunch of

424
00:25:05.232 --> 00:25:09.032
vesicles together on a surface, you might get cross-mixing of these

425
00:25:09.092 --> 00:25:12.652
signatures, so you might have single positive EVs next to each other, and it look

426
00:25:12.732 --> 00:25:14.612
like a double positive. So we

427
00:25:16.012 --> 00:25:19.792
used an alternative assay technology, this is based on MST's

428
00:25:19.852 --> 00:25:20.652
ECL

429
00:25:21.632 --> 00:25:23.292
planar array platform.

430
00:25:24.172 --> 00:25:27.552
And we measured the same samples, and we showed really high correlation, so a

431
00:25:27.612 --> 00:25:29.232
Pearson correlation of over 0.9.

432
00:25:31.252 --> 00:25:35.032
And so this was great. It kind of validated that the markers we're seeing are

433
00:25:35.072 --> 00:25:38.792
real, but it also gives us a pipeline so we can

434
00:25:38.852 --> 00:25:42.772
do our discovery of multimarker signatures using this high-multiplex

435
00:25:43.152 --> 00:25:47.062
combinatorial immunosequencing, and then once we find the interesting populations,

436
00:25:47.472 --> 00:25:51.312
we can port those over onto the ECL, the targeted assays

437
00:25:51.772 --> 00:25:55.752
for... These are lower plex, but we can run higher throughput and use

438
00:25:55.772 --> 00:25:56.652
this for validation.

439
00:25:59.452 --> 00:26:01.952
So the next question in our mind was,

440
00:26:03.212 --> 00:26:03.672
can we

441
00:26:04.952 --> 00:26:07.932
get prognostic information from some of these surface signatures?

442
00:26:09.052 --> 00:26:12.912
So we know they were elevated in cancers relative to normals, but that's not

443
00:26:12.952 --> 00:26:16.332
that useful. So we wanted to see in these longitudinal cohorts, are they actually

444
00:26:16.352 --> 00:26:19.712
predictive of overall survival or progression-free survival?

445
00:26:20.712 --> 00:26:21.702
So to

446
00:26:22.832 --> 00:26:26.332
sort of limit the scope, we took the top 100 signatures that were

447
00:26:26.412 --> 00:26:29.872
overexpressed in the tumors, and we

448
00:26:30.152 --> 00:26:31.792
performed Cox regressions on these.

449
00:26:34.032 --> 00:26:35.392
And we found there were quite a few after

450
00:26:36.392 --> 00:26:40.252
our correction for multiple comparisons, there were quite a few that

451
00:26:40.272 --> 00:26:43.092
were still FDR significant. And

452
00:26:43.112 --> 00:26:46.752
I guess one thing that's interesting, we're

453
00:26:46.772 --> 00:26:50.632
getting a number of consistent three-marker findings between the two different

454
00:26:50.692 --> 00:26:54.632
cohorts, but we're also identifying some unique three-marker

455
00:26:54.712 --> 00:26:58.672
combinations that only show up in one of these cohorts or that only show up in

456
00:26:58.732 --> 00:27:02.012
one context, either in progression-free or overall survival.

457
00:27:02.932 --> 00:27:06.392
So this gives us hope that we can make something useful out of

458
00:27:06.432 --> 00:27:07.612
this technology.

459
00:27:08.452 --> 00:27:10.492
And I guess I want to highlight a few key findings.

460
00:27:10.512 --> 00:27:14.472
We found that CD73, CD13, and CEA are kind

461
00:27:14.512 --> 00:27:17.232
of recurrent components in these

462
00:27:17.572 --> 00:27:20.972
CRC-secreted vesicles.

463
00:27:22.432 --> 00:27:26.112
All right. So to kind of sum it up, we built a technology that allows us to

464
00:27:26.132 --> 00:27:29.052
profile three-marker EV surface identities.

465
00:27:30.532 --> 00:27:34.452
We have currently, this says 63, but at this point, we're well over 100 surface

466
00:27:34.532 --> 00:27:37.852
markers, and we can do this by using the three-marker combinations.

467
00:27:38.032 --> 00:27:41.632
We can simultaneously assay tens of thousands of

468
00:27:41.692 --> 00:27:43.102
subpopulations in a single

469
00:27:43.232 --> 00:27:46.882
sample. We've

470
00:27:46.912 --> 00:27:50.232
cross-validated the technology by using an orthogonal

471
00:27:50.252 --> 00:27:53.792
platform to look at some of these populations that we found.

472
00:27:55.052 --> 00:27:56.232
And we've consistently found

473
00:27:58.032 --> 00:28:00.412
the same markers across three different CRC cohorts.

474
00:28:00.672 --> 00:28:04.492
So obviously, this isn't validation, but it gives us a signal that's at

475
00:28:04.512 --> 00:28:08.352
least reproducible in some independent sample sets.

476
00:28:09.032 --> 00:28:10.512
So interestingly, we can

477
00:28:11.672 --> 00:28:13.352
probe two different tumor compartments.

478
00:28:14.132 --> 00:28:17.712
We've seen there's prognostic value of some of these signatures.

479
00:28:18.662 --> 00:28:20.292
So what comes next? Well,

480
00:28:22.152 --> 00:28:25.672
I had been discouraged about using EVs for early detection

481
00:28:26.012 --> 00:28:29.892
simply because there are so many EVs in plasma that are not the ones you're

482
00:28:29.932 --> 00:28:33.712
looking for. So it's really hard. You're looking for essentially a few EVs

483
00:28:33.832 --> 00:28:34.892
in maybe trillions.

484
00:28:35.972 --> 00:28:39.932
But seeing the specificity we have with the multimarker gives me hope that we can

485
00:28:39.972 --> 00:28:43.152
go back to early detection. So we've started working with a few different

486
00:28:43.772 --> 00:28:45.572
cancer types, not just colorectal cancer.

487
00:28:46.232 --> 00:28:50.152
We're also interested in expanding our library of antibodies

488
00:28:50.732 --> 00:28:54.512
to look at the broader tumor microenvironment to kind of decode

489
00:28:54.522 --> 00:28:58.212
the composition of that microenvironment based on the circulating

490
00:28:58.252 --> 00:28:58.642
EVs.

491
00:28:59.652 --> 00:29:03.172
And then lastly, we want to try to track the tumor

492
00:29:03.212 --> 00:29:06.852
progression by looking at the evolution of these EV surface signatures over

493
00:29:06.952 --> 00:29:07.232
time.

494
00:29:08.352 --> 00:29:12.192
So overall, we've put together a multimarker profiling technique

495
00:29:12.312 --> 00:29:15.152
that we think opens new dimensions for analyzing liquid biopsies.

496
00:29:15.922 --> 00:29:19.712
It helps to capture the tumor ecosystem complexity in a way that single

497
00:29:19.812 --> 00:29:22.032
analyses can't resolve.

498
00:29:23.272 --> 00:29:26.132
So I want to thank my group and

499
00:29:26.992 --> 00:29:30.872
our collaborators, the Coffey Lab, the Nixon Lab, and the Cody Lab at Washington

500
00:29:30.912 --> 00:29:32.672
University, as well as our funding.

501
00:29:32.752 --> 00:29:36.142
A lot of this came from the Common Fund, the Extracellular RNA Communication

502
00:29:36.192 --> 00:29:39.692
Consortium, which supported our work for about five years.

503
00:29:39.972 --> 00:29:42.112
So thanks for listening. Take questions.

504
00:29:46.072 --> 00:29:47.652
Okay. Do we have any questions?

505
00:29:51.312 --> 00:29:55.132
I'll jump in right-- And so in terms of validation, what

506
00:29:55.312 --> 00:29:56.692
are your plans? Are you going to...

507
00:29:58.252 --> 00:30:00.392
Honestly, I'm a technology development guy.

508
00:30:00.472 --> 00:30:03.732
It's what gets me excited more so than the actual biology.

509
00:30:04.392 --> 00:30:07.372
But Lucy, who's in the audience there, she's a cancer biologist, and so she's

510
00:30:09.012 --> 00:30:09.692
going to help with that.

511
00:30:10.012 --> 00:30:10.232
Okay.

512
00:30:11.032 --> 00:30:14.372
Yeah. I'm not entirely sure. As well as our clinical collaborators will sort of

513
00:30:14.412 --> 00:30:16.432
help guide that.

514
00:30:16.492 --> 00:30:16.892
Very cool.

515
00:30:18.272 --> 00:30:18.951
All right. Thank you.

516
00:30:19.072 --> 00:30:19.932
All right. Thank you very much.

517
00:30:23.962 --> 00:30:27.382
All right. Our next speaker, Dr. Soto

518
00:30:27.742 --> 00:30:29.522
Trujillo. I hope I'm saying that correctly.

519
00:30:29.552 --> 00:30:33.482
"Differences in Survival Outcomes Among Metastatic Colorectal Cancer Patients

520
00:30:33.542 --> 00:30:37.142
Across Fibroblast Growth Factor Receptor Two and Three Expression Levels."

521
00:30:40.442 --> 00:30:42.681
Thank you, Dr. Gulveru, for welcoming me onto stage.

522
00:30:43.462 --> 00:30:46.522
My name is Steve Soto, and it is an honor for me to speak before all of you today.

523
00:30:47.202 --> 00:30:51.102
I'm a post-bac research trainee at the USC Norris Center, and today I will be

524
00:30:51.122 --> 00:30:54.702
discussing survival outcomes in metastatic colorectal cancer patients across

525
00:30:54.822 --> 00:30:57.202
FGFR2 and 3 expression levels.

526
00:30:58.542 --> 00:30:59.522
This is my disclosure.

527
00:31:00.822 --> 00:31:04.642
So colorectal cancer is the second most common cause of cancer deaths in men and

528
00:31:04.702 --> 00:31:08.502
women combined in the US. In 2026, it is estimated that

529
00:31:08.582 --> 00:31:11.762
over 150,000 people will be diagnosed with colorectal

530
00:31:11.802 --> 00:31:15.762
cancer within the US. The rise of incidents, especially in young adults,

531
00:31:15.782 --> 00:31:18.402
has only accelerated the demand for more clinical

532
00:31:18.482 --> 00:31:22.262
biomarkers. So FGFR2 and 3

533
00:31:22.282 --> 00:31:26.182
belong to the FGF receptor family, which contain a total of four

534
00:31:26.382 --> 00:31:30.172
distinct receptors recognized in the literature that bind to a diverse set of

535
00:31:30.402 --> 00:31:31.782
22 FGF ligands.

536
00:31:32.962 --> 00:31:36.802
FGFR2 and 3 are receptor tyrosine kinases that dimerize

537
00:31:36.862 --> 00:31:40.602
and autophosphorylate upon ligand binding, activating a series of

538
00:31:40.642 --> 00:31:44.342
metabolic cascades. Many of these downstream signaling pathways, similar to those

539
00:31:44.352 --> 00:31:48.302
activated by other receptors as well, such as the epidermal growth factor

540
00:31:48.322 --> 00:31:51.162
receptor and the vasoendothelial growth factor receptor.

541
00:31:52.942 --> 00:31:56.922
So FGFR2 is mostly discussed in breast cancer literature, with

542
00:31:56.942 --> 00:32:00.602
some germline variants being associated with a predisposition for breast cancer

543
00:32:00.662 --> 00:32:04.382
development. FGFR2 has been found to be expressed in the endothelium

544
00:32:04.722 --> 00:32:08.462
and has most recently been suggested in allowing dormant breast cancer tumor

545
00:32:08.502 --> 00:32:11.902
cells to survive following targeted therapy.

546
00:32:12.322 --> 00:32:15.582
The role of FGFR2 in colorectal cancer pathogenesis

547
00:32:16.042 --> 00:32:20.002
remains a bit unclear, although some papers do suggest it being linked to a more

548
00:32:20.022 --> 00:32:23.602
aggressive type of cancer and consequently worse survival outcomes.

549
00:32:25.442 --> 00:32:28.842
FGFR3 is mostly discussed in bladder cancer, with some

550
00:32:28.902 --> 00:32:32.362
specific mutations being associated with improved survival.

551
00:32:32.382 --> 00:32:36.282
While the underlying mechanisms are a bit unknown, some papers do point towards the

552
00:32:36.362 --> 00:32:40.142
possible modulation of the tumor microenvironment through the infiltration

553
00:32:40.202 --> 00:32:41.242
of T cells.

554
00:32:42.282 --> 00:32:45.942
FGFR3 gene alterations have been found to be increased in a small CRC

555
00:32:45.982 --> 00:32:48.922
cohort, although this failed to be statistically significant.

556
00:32:50.642 --> 00:32:54.292
So based on the literature for FGFR2 and FGFR3, our team

557
00:32:54.302 --> 00:32:58.022
hypothesized that in colorectal cancer patients, FGFR2 gene

558
00:32:58.062 --> 00:33:01.982
expression will be associated with worse survival due to a possible contributing

559
00:33:02.022 --> 00:33:05.542
factor towards angiogenesis, and FGFR3 gene expression will be

560
00:33:05.562 --> 00:33:09.542
associated with improved survival due to this possible modulation of the

561
00:33:09.582 --> 00:33:10.682
tumor microenvironment.

562
00:33:12.862 --> 00:33:16.122
So the database in which we conducted our analysis in is the

563
00:33:16.182 --> 00:33:19.922
CALGB SWOG 80405 Phase III clinical trial,

564
00:33:20.452 --> 00:33:24.022
which contained a cohort of newly diagnosed metastatic colorectal cancer

565
00:33:24.102 --> 00:33:28.042
patients that were randomly assigned to a chemotherapy plus cetuximab treatment

566
00:33:28.162 --> 00:33:31.662
arm or a chemotherapy plus bevacizumab treatment arm.

567
00:33:32.042 --> 00:33:35.702
So cetuximab is a monoclonal antibody for the epidermal growth factor

568
00:33:35.742 --> 00:33:39.522
receptor, which is responsible for cell survival, and

569
00:33:39.542 --> 00:33:43.202
bevacizumab is a monoclonal antibody for the vasoendothelial growth

570
00:33:43.262 --> 00:33:45.942
factor, which is strongly linked to angiogenesis.

571
00:33:46.622 --> 00:33:50.082
Other covariates that we adjusted for in our additional statistical

572
00:33:50.142 --> 00:33:54.072
analysis include the KRAS mutation, BRAF mutation, and

573
00:33:54.282 --> 00:33:55.062
MSI status,

574
00:33:56.102 --> 00:33:58.442
sidedness, age, sex, chemotherapy as well.

575
00:34:00.222 --> 00:34:04.162
So we initially tested for the prognostic potential of FGFR2 by

576
00:34:04.202 --> 00:34:06.142
grouping our two treatment arms together.

577
00:34:06.742 --> 00:34:10.002
So here on the left side, we have a progression-free survival curve

578
00:34:10.263 --> 00:34:13.902
where FGFR2 high expression was somewhat associated with

579
00:34:15.082 --> 00:34:18.522
worse survival. However, this failed to be statistically

580
00:34:18.582 --> 00:34:22.243
significant. However, FGFR2 did demonstrate to

581
00:34:22.283 --> 00:34:25.783
be prognostic of overall survival across our treatment

582
00:34:25.882 --> 00:34:29.872
arms, with FGFR2 high expression being associated with worse survival, with

583
00:34:29.882 --> 00:34:33.102
the median survival difference between FGFR2 high and low

584
00:34:33.803 --> 00:34:37.502
7.4 months and the hazard ratio of high to low 1.28,

585
00:34:38.022 --> 00:34:41.911
meaning that our FGFR2 high expression group had a 28% increased chance of

586
00:34:41.922 --> 00:34:43.062
mortality at any time.

587
00:34:45.582 --> 00:34:49.542
So to determine if these effects observed in our

588
00:34:49.562 --> 00:34:53.522
prognostic curves were more pronounced in a specific treatment arm, we

589
00:34:53.562 --> 00:34:55.882
looked at each treatment arm individually.

590
00:34:55.902 --> 00:34:59.602
So here on the left side, we found that FGFR2 was not predictive of

591
00:34:59.642 --> 00:35:03.522
overall survival in patients being treated with bevacizumab, which was striking

592
00:35:03.562 --> 00:35:07.522
because bevacizumab being an anti-angiogenic drug and FGFR2

593
00:35:07.532 --> 00:35:11.462
being strongly linked towards angiogenesis, we expected FGFR2 gene expression

594
00:35:11.502 --> 00:35:15.282
to have a greater predictability in clinical response.

595
00:35:15.362 --> 00:35:19.342
However, FGFR2 gene expression was predictive of overall survival

596
00:35:19.362 --> 00:35:21.102
in patients being treated with cetuximab,

597
00:35:22.182 --> 00:35:25.782
with FGFR2 high expression being associated with worse survival

598
00:35:26.582 --> 00:35:30.442
and the median survival difference between high and low being 12 months and the

599
00:35:30.482 --> 00:35:34.122
hazard ratio of high to low 1.56, meaning that our

600
00:35:34.262 --> 00:35:38.042
FGFR2 high expression group had a 56% increased chance of

601
00:35:38.062 --> 00:35:39.182
mortality at any time.

602
00:35:41.242 --> 00:35:44.892
So we then conducted a similar analysis for the FGFR3 gene expression,

603
00:35:45.382 --> 00:35:48.762
but did not find it to be prognostic of overall nor progression-free

604
00:35:48.822 --> 00:35:50.932
survival across our treatment arms.

605
00:35:51.402 --> 00:35:55.182
However, we did find that FGFR3 gene expression was predictive of

606
00:35:55.222 --> 00:35:55.982
overall survival

607
00:35:57.122 --> 00:35:58.922
in patients being treated with cetuximab.

608
00:35:59.102 --> 00:36:02.942
However, in this case, FGFR3 high expression was associated with

609
00:36:03.042 --> 00:36:06.542
improved survival, with the median survival difference of high to low being

610
00:36:06.562 --> 00:36:10.412
12.4 months and the hazard ratio of high to low 0.59,

611
00:36:10.882 --> 00:36:14.602
meaning that there was a 41% reduction in mortality in our FGFR3 high

612
00:36:14.662 --> 00:36:15.432
expression group.

613
00:36:18.102 --> 00:36:21.982
We then tested for differences in FGFR2 and

614
00:36:22.342 --> 00:36:26.182
FGFR3 gene expression across ethnicity and race and found no statistically

615
00:36:26.262 --> 00:36:29.818
significant differenceNor did we find any difference in early

616
00:36:29.898 --> 00:36:32.678
onset versus late onset colorectal cancer patients.

617
00:36:34.698 --> 00:36:38.438
So we then moved on to SNPs. SNPs are single nucleotide polymorphisms,

618
00:36:38.898 --> 00:36:42.608
which are genetic variants that differ from each other by a single nucleotide and

619
00:36:42.618 --> 00:36:46.518
whose functional impact varies depending on the site of the mutation.

620
00:36:46.578 --> 00:36:50.568
So SNPs can manifest themselves as either a heterozygous variant if

621
00:36:50.618 --> 00:36:54.478
a mutant allele is inherited from one parent, or a homozygous variant if

622
00:36:54.538 --> 00:36:56.458
two mutant alleles are inherited from both parents.

623
00:36:56.828 --> 00:37:00.498
So here we sourced 12 distinct SNPs recognized in the literature for

624
00:37:00.598 --> 00:37:03.158
FGFR2 and FGFR3 and tested

625
00:37:04.218 --> 00:37:06.038
their associations with survival.

626
00:37:07.918 --> 00:37:10.598
So here we have a visualization of one of those analyses.

627
00:37:11.018 --> 00:37:14.518
Here we tested for the prognostic potential of the SNP in FGFR2,

628
00:37:15.078 --> 00:37:18.988
RS-3135718, and found that the variant allele groups,

629
00:37:19.078 --> 00:37:22.578
the heterozygous variant and the homozygous variant on the left curve, do seem to

630
00:37:22.618 --> 00:37:24.358
be associated with improved survival.

631
00:37:24.818 --> 00:37:28.578
However, this failed to be significant in the overall survival curve, although

632
00:37:28.598 --> 00:37:30.238
there does seem to be a similar pattern.

633
00:37:32.038 --> 00:37:35.998
We then looked at each treatment arm individually and found that this SNP was not

634
00:37:36.018 --> 00:37:39.258
predictive of survival in patients being treated with

635
00:37:39.278 --> 00:37:40.098
bevacizumab.

636
00:37:41.478 --> 00:37:45.358
However, we did find that the SNP was predictive of progression-free and

637
00:37:45.438 --> 00:37:47.818
overall survival in patients being treated with cetuximab.

638
00:37:48.358 --> 00:37:52.038
So here in the overall survival curve, we see that the heterozygous variant group,

639
00:37:52.238 --> 00:37:55.968
the blue curve, is associated with improved survival, and the homozygous variant,

640
00:37:56.118 --> 00:37:59.438
the red curve, is associated with the highest improvement in survival relative to

641
00:37:59.498 --> 00:38:01.438
the heterozygous and the wild type group,

642
00:38:02.318 --> 00:38:05.758
with the median survival difference between the homozygous variant and the wild

643
00:38:05.858 --> 00:38:09.678
type being three months. So while the difference in survival is not grand,

644
00:38:09.778 --> 00:38:13.458
it does suggest that this SNP may have some sort of functional role in

645
00:38:13.498 --> 00:38:16.858
predicting clinical response in patients being treated with cetuximab.

646
00:38:17.598 --> 00:38:21.058
I think it is important to note that here in the overall survival curve, from zero

647
00:38:21.138 --> 00:38:25.018
to 29 months, we don't see a clear distinction in survival between the

648
00:38:25.098 --> 00:38:28.958
three groups. It is only after 30 months and forward where we see a clear

649
00:38:28.998 --> 00:38:32.918
distinction between the three groups, suggesting that the SNP may be

650
00:38:33.878 --> 00:38:37.817
predictive only after a specific clinically relevant time point.

651
00:38:40.158 --> 00:38:43.578
So we then tested the SNP's association with its respective

652
00:38:43.738 --> 00:38:47.598
FGFR2 gene expression, but did not find any differences in gene expression

653
00:38:47.618 --> 00:38:50.638
between the three groups, the wild type, homozygous variant, or heterozygous

654
00:38:50.718 --> 00:38:54.618
variant. Nor did we find any differences in gene expression in other SNPs that we

655
00:38:54.658 --> 00:38:56.928
tested with their respective gene expression.

656
00:38:58.858 --> 00:39:02.628
So overall, in the 80405 Phase III clinical trial, we found that

657
00:39:02.758 --> 00:39:05.818
FGFR2 low expression, the SNP in FGFR2

658
00:39:05.938 --> 00:39:09.898
RS-3135718, and the FGFR3 high expression

659
00:39:09.918 --> 00:39:13.558
were all strongly predictive of survival in patients being treated with cetuximab,

660
00:39:14.018 --> 00:39:16.308
with them all being strongly associated with improved survival.

661
00:39:18.138 --> 00:39:22.088
So given the biomarker potential promised by

662
00:39:22.178 --> 00:39:25.998
our predictive and prognostic curves, we have transitioned to a pre-clinical

663
00:39:26.078 --> 00:39:29.678
platform in an effort to elucidate the underlying mechanisms

664
00:39:29.698 --> 00:39:32.738
surrounding FGFR2 and FGFR3 signaling.

665
00:39:33.198 --> 00:39:34.558
So here on the right side, we

666
00:39:35.478 --> 00:39:39.158
inhibited FGFR2 in various CRC cell lines with

667
00:39:39.258 --> 00:39:42.798
unique molecular characteristics and successfully decreased cell

668
00:39:42.838 --> 00:39:46.798
viability, reiterating the criticality of FGFR2 in

669
00:39:46.858 --> 00:39:50.398
maintaining cell survival in these human-derived CRC cell lines.

670
00:39:52.158 --> 00:39:55.968
So thank you so much to my PI, Dr. Lenz, and everyone else on the part of the

671
00:39:56.038 --> 00:39:58.098
team that made this project and presentation possible.

672
00:39:58.518 --> 00:40:02.318
Thank you to patients and caregivers for their invaluable contribution

673
00:40:02.378 --> 00:40:05.058
to this Phase III clinical trial.

674
00:40:05.958 --> 00:40:06.278
Thank you.

675
00:40:09.498 --> 00:40:11.318
Excellent. It's now open for discussion.

676
00:40:13.498 --> 00:40:17.158
Thank you. Very nice talk. I was wondering, you tested also

677
00:40:17.698 --> 00:40:21.118
SNPs in FGFR3. Were any of those SNPs associated with outcome?

678
00:40:21.698 --> 00:40:25.498
We did not find any of the SNPs that I-- Those 12 SNPs that I mentioned,

679
00:40:26.278 --> 00:40:29.948
those of FGFR3, we did not find any to be statistically significant with their-

680
00:40:30.158 --> 00:40:30.628
All right. Thank you

681
00:40:30.628 --> 00:40:32.718
... respective gene express-- or survival.

682
00:40:39.278 --> 00:40:42.938
Well, a quick question. So, given that FGFR2 and

683
00:40:43.118 --> 00:40:46.878
R3 are from the same family, why do you think that they behave differently?

684
00:40:47.718 --> 00:40:51.058
So I think that's what makes the findings from this

685
00:40:51.138 --> 00:40:54.968
analysis very exciting. The fact that they're part of the FGF, they're

686
00:40:54.968 --> 00:40:58.798
both RTKs or receptor tyrosine kinase, but they could be

687
00:40:58.858 --> 00:41:02.398
associated with different survival outcomes, makes it even more intriguing,

688
00:41:02.818 --> 00:41:06.798
and is what we are basically trying to work on next

689
00:41:06.838 --> 00:41:10.638
in these other clinical experiments that we are planning for soon.

690
00:41:11.918 --> 00:41:13.298
Great. Thank you very much.

691
00:41:16.458 --> 00:41:17.688
See, I think it's me. Is it me or you?

692
00:41:17.688 --> 00:41:18.148
It's you.

693
00:41:18.198 --> 00:41:22.038
Okay. Okay, so the next speaker is Lubna Ahmad,

694
00:41:23.418 --> 00:41:26.358
who is here from the University of Cambridge, and she will be talking about the

695
00:41:26.398 --> 00:41:30.358
mapping of spatial organization of B cells and immune signaling in triple

696
00:41:30.398 --> 00:41:33.958
negative breast cancer to characterize response to immunotherapy.

697
00:41:45.348 --> 00:41:49.078
Good afternoon, everybody. My name is Lubna, and today

698
00:41:49.238 --> 00:41:52.958
I'm... So first of all, I'm a postdoc in the Ali Lab at the Cancer Research

699
00:41:53.038 --> 00:41:56.818
UK Cambridge Institute, and I'm talking a little bit about my PhD

700
00:41:56.838 --> 00:42:00.758
project, which looked at B cells and immune signaling in an immunotherapy

701
00:42:00.838 --> 00:42:03.258
trial to characterize response to treatment.

702
00:42:04.498 --> 00:42:04.718
So,

703
00:42:06.238 --> 00:42:10.128
to set the stage, so the main kind of challenge we have in immunotherapy is

704
00:42:10.198 --> 00:42:13.988
how can we better predict which patients are going to respond to this treatment?

705
00:42:14.878 --> 00:42:18.618
Essentially, in solid tumors, what we do, we assess

706
00:42:18.658 --> 00:42:19.258
PD-L1

707
00:42:20.178 --> 00:42:23.638
expression, and that is usually done by scoring its staining across

708
00:42:23.658 --> 00:42:25.298
tumor-infiltrating immune cells.

709
00:42:26.018 --> 00:42:29.638
However, emerging clinical evidence has suggested that this does not really

710
00:42:29.698 --> 00:42:33.658
capture the complexity of responses and that additional features

711
00:42:33.678 --> 00:42:37.198
of the TME might be important to take into account.

712
00:42:37.648 --> 00:42:41.058
So in the recent years, B cells have become increasingly associated with

713
00:42:41.098 --> 00:42:44.798
immunotherapy response, such as in studies of melanoma, renal cell

714
00:42:44.858 --> 00:42:48.846
carcinoma, and sarcoma.Despite the growing interest

715
00:42:48.886 --> 00:42:51.486
in B cells, B cells in cancer are generally

716
00:42:51.526 --> 00:42:54.366
relatively poorly characterized.

717
00:42:54.466 --> 00:42:58.146
For example, in terms of their heterogeneity, very little is known about the

718
00:42:58.186 --> 00:43:01.516
composition, localization, maturation, and molecular characteristics.

719
00:43:02.036 --> 00:43:05.716
So although we know that B cells seem to matter, we know very little

720
00:43:05.766 --> 00:43:09.636
of how, when, or why they contribute to responses in

721
00:43:09.726 --> 00:43:13.486
cancer. So to address some of these questions, I use an approach called

722
00:43:13.546 --> 00:43:16.086
imaging mass cytometry. So here, I

723
00:43:17.306 --> 00:43:20.986
made a targeted panel that looked at B-cell protein markers, cytokine

724
00:43:21.086 --> 00:43:24.326
RNA markers, and other contextual protein markers.

725
00:43:24.786 --> 00:43:28.506
I used FFPE tissue where I used double Z probes to target the

726
00:43:28.586 --> 00:43:32.566
RNA of these cytokines. And I amplified the signal

727
00:43:32.626 --> 00:43:36.186
using a branch DNA structure, which was modified to be labeled with

728
00:43:36.306 --> 00:43:39.935
metal-conjugated labeling probes in order to detect the signal using

729
00:43:40.006 --> 00:43:43.926
IMC. After this, the tissue is then stained with a cocktail

730
00:43:43.986 --> 00:43:45.615
of metal-conjugated antibodies.

731
00:43:46.186 --> 00:43:49.846
I then identify regions of interest which are ablated at one micron

732
00:43:49.886 --> 00:43:53.406
