clonal tumors in the lung that we can now resolve

1457
01:25:45.234 --> 01:25:46.754
spatially directly in the tissue.

1458
01:25:49.454 --> 01:25:53.184
And so this is essentially how we do this kind of workflow,

1459
01:25:53.264 --> 01:25:56.874
and the really great thing about this methodology is that it's compatible with

1460
01:25:56.914 --> 01:26:00.734
multimodal tissue profiling. So you get the high throughput, the high scale of in

1461
01:26:00.774 --> 01:26:03.814
vivo, but without compromising on any of the phenotyping that you want to do.

1462
01:26:04.874 --> 01:26:08.574
So, an example here is that you can use antibodies to detect the epitope

1463
01:26:08.634 --> 01:26:12.484
tags, in which case you can combine this with a whole panel of multiplex IF

1464
01:26:12.774 --> 01:26:15.614
to study your favorite biology in the TME.

1465
01:26:16.254 --> 01:26:19.614
And then very recently, we've been partnering with Bluco Spatial Biology, and they

1466
01:26:19.654 --> 01:26:23.594
have designed probes that can directly recognize the RNA molecules of

1467
01:26:23.614 --> 01:26:27.494
these barcodes. And as you can see here, you can very clearly also delineate all

1468
01:26:27.514 --> 01:26:31.414
the clonal tumors. And for each one of these tumors, we have access to

1469
01:26:31.494 --> 01:26:35.194
the genetic perturbation that is carried by the cells, and we also have access to

1470
01:26:35.234 --> 01:26:37.494
the spatial transcriptomics data.

1471
01:26:37.534 --> 01:26:39.374
And in this case, it's actually the whole transcriptome

1472
01:26:40.294 --> 01:26:41.254
that was generated.

1473
01:26:42.474 --> 01:26:45.754
And so we have the first piece of the puzzle. We can ask a lot of questions.

1474
01:26:45.814 --> 01:26:49.774
We can screen all these different genetic perturbations, and we can

1475
01:26:49.794 --> 01:26:52.674
do that with multimodal tissue profiling.

1476
01:26:53.354 --> 01:26:55.614
But this is still studying mouse biology.

1477
01:26:55.934 --> 01:26:59.214
And the second really important element that we want to have is that we want to

1478
01:26:59.274 --> 01:27:00.914
impact patients' lives at the end of the day.

1479
01:27:01.484 --> 01:27:04.464
So we need to have a way to analyze this data in a way that will speak to the

1480
01:27:04.514 --> 01:27:04.954
patients.

1481
01:27:07.154 --> 01:27:11.054
And this is where we leverage some of our foundation

1482
01:27:11.194 --> 01:27:12.294
machine learning models.

1483
01:27:13.234 --> 01:27:16.574
In this case, it's a model that has been trained exclusively on patients' data.

1484
01:27:17.284 --> 01:27:21.034
And so what the model is seeing to learn biology is aligned multimodal

1485
01:27:21.074 --> 01:27:24.934
data, which is H&amp;E and then a layer of whole transcriptomics, spatial

1486
01:27:24.954 --> 01:27:25.574
transcriptomics

1487
01:27:26.434 --> 01:27:26.974
for the same

1488
01:27:28.774 --> 01:27:29.134
tissue.

1489
01:27:30.214 --> 01:27:33.794
And so at training time, the model is going to learn human biology based on these

1490
01:27:33.814 --> 01:27:34.294
two layers.

1491
01:27:35.814 --> 01:27:39.074
At inference time, what we can do then is that we can feed the model

1492
01:27:39.674 --> 01:27:43.634
any H&amp;E image, and the model can predict and infer the expression of

1493
01:27:43.694 --> 01:27:46.894
every single gene in the spatial proteomics panel.

1494
01:27:46.954 --> 01:27:48.354
So in this case, the whole transcriptome.

1495
01:27:49.034 --> 01:27:52.914
And essentially what this does is that it turns your H&amp;E slide into

1496
01:27:53.174 --> 01:27:56.914
a spatial transcriptomics data set directly without needing to

1497
01:27:56.954 --> 01:27:57.894
actually run the assay.

1498
01:27:58.874 --> 01:28:00.834
And when I say any H&amp;E,

1499
01:28:01.694 --> 01:28:02.354
we really took it

1500
01:28:03.654 --> 01:28:07.634
to the next level, and we decided that we would just feed this model

1501
01:28:08.054 --> 01:28:08.194
the

1502
01:28:09.834 --> 01:28:13.214
H&amp;E samples from the Bertamap high-throughput in vivo platform

1503
01:28:13.694 --> 01:28:15.954
that we've been using to generate the causal data set.

1504
01:28:17.023 --> 01:28:17.854
And so we have

1505
01:28:18.794 --> 01:28:19.434
this way,

1506
01:28:20.434 --> 01:28:24.194
we feed the model with this H&amp;E. The model has been only trained on human

1507
01:28:24.214 --> 01:28:27.734
data, so the model is going to make predictions on expression of human

1508
01:28:27.754 --> 01:28:30.974
gene in the mouse model. So essentially what this does is

1509
01:28:31.154 --> 01:28:35.114
it humanizes the mouse system, but in silico after the experiment

1510
01:28:35.134 --> 01:28:38.694
has been run, and you can project human biology directly on mouse tissue.

1511
01:28:38.854 --> 01:28:42.834
So this is what we have called a MALS for multi-species alignment and

1512
01:28:42.874 --> 01:28:46.654
reasoning on spatial data, because our model, even though it's trained on human

1513
01:28:46.694 --> 01:28:49.194
data, is agnostic to the species you run it on.

1514
01:28:51.434 --> 01:28:55.334
How does that look like? So this is an example where, again, we project

1515
01:28:55.374 --> 01:28:58.594
the human signature on the tissue, and you can see here on the H&amp;E that you have

1516
01:28:59.894 --> 01:29:03.494
some tumor nodules in the tissue. And the model is actually

1517
01:29:03.954 --> 01:29:07.774
very able to identify where the tumors are located because this is where the

1518
01:29:07.814 --> 01:29:10.834
model is going to predict that there is a very high human keratin-17

1519
01:29:10.874 --> 01:29:14.714
expression. And this is because keratin-17 is a marker of the

1520
01:29:14.754 --> 01:29:17.314
human lung cancer that the model has been trained on.

1521
01:29:17.854 --> 01:29:21.034
And as you can see, this matches perfectly the ground truth staining of

1522
01:29:22.074 --> 01:29:24.314
the tumor marker that we use in this mouse model.

1523
01:29:28.014 --> 01:29:31.874
What's really interesting here is that, again, the model only understands human

1524
01:29:31.934 --> 01:29:33.814
biology and only projects human biology.

1525
01:29:33.884 --> 01:29:37.214
So in this case, in this example, what we've looked at is the expression of CCAM6.

1526
01:29:38.634 --> 01:29:42.523
And you may know that CCAM6 is a gene that

1527
01:29:42.554 --> 01:29:45.394
does not have an ortholog in mice. So this gene doesn't exist in mice.

1528
01:29:46.014 --> 01:29:49.334
If you're very interested in that, if you have therapeutics program against CCAM6,

1529
01:29:50.694 --> 01:29:54.234
you can't really measure its expression in the mouse tissue, in the preclinical

1530
01:29:54.273 --> 01:29:54.594
tissue.

1531
01:29:55.454 --> 01:29:58.634
In this case, though, the model is perfectly able to predict

1532
01:29:59.534 --> 01:30:03.494
what are the tumors that are going to express higher level of this gene.

1533
01:30:04.054 --> 01:30:07.614
And you can see that most tumors here are comparing to the H&amp;E on the left.

1534
01:30:08.354 --> 01:30:11.814
Most tumors have very low to no CCAM6 expression at baseline.

1535
01:30:12.134 --> 01:30:15.684
But we have found that a specific tumor here on the bottom left and

1536
01:30:15.754 --> 01:30:19.274
magnified here in the center is actually characterized with a high level of

1537
01:30:19.354 --> 01:30:22.054
predicted human CCAM6 expression.

1538
01:30:22.694 --> 01:30:25.714
And what we find that we look at the knockouts, it's a knockout of a transcription

1539
01:30:25.794 --> 01:30:29.594
factor that essentially is going to induce a switch in histology of the tumor.

1540
01:30:30.114 --> 01:30:33.864
And the resulting histology resembles the tumor

1541
01:30:33.914 --> 01:30:36.554
histology in patients that have high CCAM6 expression.

1542
01:30:39.894 --> 01:30:43.074
And so, as I mentioned before, we've generated a very large data set of more than

1543
01:30:43.314 --> 01:30:46.414
600 different genetic perturbations across different therapeutics.

1544
01:30:47.554 --> 01:30:50.534
And so the idea then was, how do we analyze this in a way that we can

1545
01:30:50.754 --> 01:30:54.514
access the diversity of the mouse phenotype that we have generated?

1546
01:30:55.254 --> 01:30:59.054
And so the model is only seeing the H&amp;E and is completely

1547
01:30:59.074 --> 01:31:02.994
blind to the perturbation, but we have the perturbation label on top of

1548
01:31:03.034 --> 01:31:06.334
this H&amp;E as well. So what we are doing is that we are aggregating the signatures

1549
01:31:06.394 --> 01:31:09.454
for every tumor that has the same clonal perturbation.

1550
01:31:10.274 --> 01:31:14.134
And then all these tumors end up being one spot here in this

1551
01:31:14.454 --> 01:31:16.534
2D space, which we call an embedding space.

1552
01:31:17.114 --> 01:31:20.374
And so the way to look at this figure on the right is that each single dot

1553
01:31:21.114 --> 01:31:24.654
corresponds to the phenotype of one genetic knockout in a

1554
01:31:24.714 --> 01:31:26.314
particular therapeutic setting.

1555
01:31:26.354 --> 01:31:29.954
So it could be a beta-2M knockout in an isotype control or a

1556
01:31:29.994 --> 01:31:33.274
beta-2M knockout in animals treated with anti-PD-1, for

1557
01:31:33.314 --> 01:31:37.182
example.And then on top of this space, we can

1558
01:31:37.262 --> 01:31:40.942
add a number of labels. We can just represent, in this case, the expression

1559
01:31:41.022 --> 01:31:44.722
of predicted human HER2 on top of the space.

1560
01:31:44.782 --> 01:31:48.282
You see that the knockouts that are here on the right are characterized by a higher

1561
01:31:48.302 --> 01:31:51.742
expression of HER2, whereas the ones on the left in blue have a lower expression of

1562
01:31:51.762 --> 01:31:52.182
HER2.

1563
01:31:57.022 --> 01:32:00.942
And so using this embedding space here, what we can

1564
01:32:01.002 --> 01:32:04.942
do now is also try to understand, we have a diverse mouse biology,

1565
01:32:05.022 --> 01:32:08.682
we have the human biology projecting on top of that, and we've done some work to

1566
01:32:08.722 --> 01:32:12.672
understand what are the main drivers of the diversity of phenotype

1567
01:32:12.672 --> 01:32:15.562
that we find here. So we know, for example, that there's a given cluster here that

1568
01:32:15.602 --> 01:32:19.522
is very specific of a certain metabolic

1569
01:32:19.542 --> 01:32:23.042
signature, for example, that we find in some patients and that we can reproduce

1570
01:32:23.062 --> 01:32:26.842
here in the mouse model. Another big axis of viability is

1571
01:32:26.902 --> 01:32:30.122
the immune infiltration gene signature, where you find that

1572
01:32:31.262 --> 01:32:35.222
the left of the space here is characterized by a

1573
01:32:35.242 --> 01:32:38.922
knockout that have a very low immune efficient signature, so low

1574
01:32:39.502 --> 01:32:43.042
T cell activity. And they actually have also an increased

1575
01:32:43.442 --> 01:32:46.982
fibrotic signature there. And then the ones that are here on the right

1576
01:32:47.802 --> 01:32:49.702
are characterized by the higher T cell activity.

1577
01:32:51.102 --> 01:32:54.482
And we can then also map all these knockouts to where they are in the space.

1578
01:32:54.522 --> 01:32:58.342
So we can identify which are the knockouts, which are the perturbations that are

1579
01:32:58.382 --> 01:33:01.822
going to drive these phenotypes. And when we do this, what we find is that we find

1580
01:33:01.862 --> 01:33:05.352
a lot of established biology that we know in patients to be true.

1581
01:33:06.302 --> 01:33:10.162
We find, for example, STK11 knockout tumors tend to

1582
01:33:10.202 --> 01:33:11.782
be very cold and have a bit

1583
01:33:12.722 --> 01:33:13.342
more fibrotic.

1584
01:33:14.242 --> 01:33:16.462
beta2m knockout tumors have also low T cells.

1585
01:33:16.882 --> 01:33:20.412
These are both mutations that are associated with lack of response to immune

1586
01:33:20.562 --> 01:33:22.602
checkpoint blockade, so this is something that makes sense.

1587
01:33:23.942 --> 01:33:27.222
And on the right part of the space, if you knockout beta-catenin,

1588
01:33:27.602 --> 01:33:31.582
SOX1, which is a negative regulator in Wnt gamma signaling, or PTPN2,

1589
01:33:31.622 --> 01:33:35.182
these are also gene knockouts that have been shown to induce

1590
01:33:35.902 --> 01:33:39.342
recruitment of T cells. And some of these other genes that are anonymized here are

1591
01:33:39.402 --> 01:33:42.802
things that are in the clinic right now or that we know that those phenotypes are

1592
01:33:42.842 --> 01:33:43.142
also

1593
01:33:43.962 --> 01:33:45.381
correlated to what we have in patients.

1594
01:33:48.702 --> 01:33:51.822
Then one way to use these models, I've mentioned before that we have

1595
01:33:53.542 --> 01:33:56.842
these knockouts both in the control isotype

1596
01:33:57.162 --> 01:34:00.762
treatment conditions, but also after immune checkpoint blockade.

1597
01:34:00.782 --> 01:34:03.522
And so what becomes interesting is that we can look at the trajectories of these

1598
01:34:03.562 --> 01:34:06.002
different knockouts upon treatment with different drugs.

1599
01:34:06.712 --> 01:34:10.662
And for example, if you here look at this knockout of VGFR1,

1600
01:34:11.682 --> 01:34:15.562
the VGFR receptor, when you treat this knockout with PD1, you

1601
01:34:15.662 --> 01:34:19.502
see a drastic shift towards the right of the space

1602
01:34:19.822 --> 01:34:23.722
of the phenotype of this tumor. So these tumors under PD1 become tumors that

1603
01:34:23.762 --> 01:34:27.162
have a very hot TME. And this gives you a very good rationale that

1604
01:34:27.762 --> 01:34:31.602
it would probably be a good idea to generate a bispecific against VEGF

1605
01:34:31.642 --> 01:34:35.282
pathway and PD1, which we know is something that has activity in the

1606
01:34:35.302 --> 01:34:35.662
clinic.

1607
01:34:37.002 --> 01:34:40.801
And another example here, this is a gene that has an

1608
01:34:40.962 --> 01:34:41.442
oncogene

1609
01:34:42.602 --> 01:34:44.102
targeted therapy target that is not

1610
01:34:45.502 --> 01:34:47.822
typically used in combination with immunotherapy.

1611
01:34:49.002 --> 01:34:51.642
And we can find the same thing here that we now have a rationale that this is

1612
01:34:51.662 --> 01:34:55.462
something that probably would be a good idea to target in

1613
01:34:55.502 --> 01:34:59.462
combination with PD1 and for example, in a bispecific format.

1614
01:35:02.862 --> 01:35:06.562
So to conclude on this, the BERTA mouse platform that we have developed

1615
01:35:07.382 --> 01:35:08.922
relies on two main characteristics.

1616
01:35:08.982 --> 01:35:12.862
The first one is that we can model tumor biology in vivo and at scale, and this

1617
01:35:12.922 --> 01:35:16.802
is allowing us to generate a large, diverse landscape of tumor

1618
01:35:16.862 --> 01:35:20.662
biology in vivo in mouse, which reflects the diversity of phenotype that you

1619
01:35:20.702 --> 01:35:21.662
also find in patients.

1620
01:35:22.642 --> 01:35:26.102
The second element is that we are able to translate that biology into human

1621
01:35:26.162 --> 01:35:30.022
biology by humanizing the non-clinical model with H&amp;E inference.

1622
01:35:30.142 --> 01:35:33.262
So we basically project the human biology on the mouse canvas,

1623
01:35:34.662 --> 01:35:37.922
and then we can use this methodology to discover next generation

1624
01:35:38.262 --> 01:35:42.102
bispecific combination targets, biomarkers, and so on.

1625
01:35:42.122 --> 01:35:44.682
And the example I showed today was on the lung

1626
01:35:45.902 --> 01:35:49.602
cancer data set and with PD1 blockade, but we are currently actively

1627
01:35:49.642 --> 01:35:53.542
expanding this on different activation indications and also

1628
01:35:53.581 --> 01:35:55.462
looking for partners in that space.

1629
01:35:56.462 --> 01:35:58.972
If you have your favorite drug and you would like to run this kind of assay, for

1630
01:35:59.022 --> 01:36:02.882
example, we can also run the exact same data set with your drug of choice and look

1631
01:36:02.922 --> 01:36:06.022
at what are the drivers of response in that case as well.

1632
01:36:07.062 --> 01:36:07.342
Thank you.

1633
01:36:12.422 --> 01:36:14.162
All right. This paper is open for discussion.

